data.title: Poldark girl Gabriella Wilde posts picture of cleavage-enhancing costume
data.meta_description: The 27-year-old, who plays aristocratic heiress Caroline Penvenen  in the BBC drama, posted this picture of her cleavage-enhancing costume in the third series, which she is filming in Cornwall.
data.text:
Poldark may be best known for Aidan Turner’s regular topless scenes, but his co-star Gabriella Wilde is determined to show that she, too, has the phwoar factor.

The 27-year-old actress, who plays aristocratic heiress Caroline Penvenen in the hit BBC period drama, yesterday posted online this picture of her cleavage-enhancing costume in the third series, which she is filming in Cornwall.

‘Back on set with Poldark,’ said Gabriella, who is the great-granddaughter of a baronet.

The former Burberry model, whose real surname is Anstruther-Gough-Calthorpe, shares a half-sister with Prince Harry’s ex-girlfriend, Cressida Bonas.

BBC star: I cut off all my hair for Helena to wear

BBC star Nick Knowles is still waiting for the chance to tell Helena Bonham Carter that she wore extensions made out of his hair in the film A Room With A View.

Best known for hosting DIY SOS, Knowles had an uncredited role in the 1985 British period drama, in which he appeared in the background of a churchyard scene.

‘My hair had a leading role — while I was only an extra,’ says Knowles, 54. ‘I played in a rock band and had really long hair, almost to my waist.

‘I went to do this day’s filming and they offered me £50 for it. I really needed the money, so I took it, even though it meant having all my hair shaved off.

‘The barber made it into extensions for Helena [pictured as Lucy Honeychurch in the film, with Julian Sands as George Emerson], as it was exactly the right colour. All those big extra curls in her hair were mine. She looked amazing. I’ve not had a chance to tell her.’

Fancy Valentine’s dinner date with dashing Luther star Idris Elba?

It could be yours in return for a donation to the charity W. E. Can Lead, which helps educate schoolgirls in Africa.

The 44-year-old Londoner, who shot to fame in U.S. crime drama The Wire, jokes that he is willing to give the most generous bidder in an online auction ‘whatever they want’ for dessert.

‘That’s right, love. Just you and me,’ says Elba in a promotional video. ‘No one else around. Just us.

'Now, we’ll get things started off with cocktails or perhaps champagne. And once we’re feeling comfortable, we can order whatever your heart desires. Maybe some truffles, perhaps some steak, pepper soup and fufu. That’s an African dish . . . And for dessert, you can have whatever you want and I mean, whatever you want.’

What a tease.

Dame Joan Collins, whose current and fifth husband Percy Gibson is a mere 32 years her junior, has messaged her support to Madonna, 58, over the latter’s penchant for younger men — she says the singer is merely following her own toyboy-loving example.

Joanie, 83, trills: ‘So Madonna reported to be with guys three decades younger than her . . . Copycat. You go, girl!’ If it’s good enough for Joan . . .

Bono and U2 are clearing their throats for the 30th anniversary Joshua Tree tour, celebrating the 1987 album of that name.

Fans have built shrines around various Joshua trees, believing them to be the original from the famous album sleeve photograph of the band in California’s Mojave Desert.

Which one is authentic? ‘None of them,’ says U2’s former manager Paul McGuinness. ‘The original tree was cut down by a souvenir hunter who brought it to a gig.’
